    <div class="panel panel-default">
      <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
          <a data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseTwo">
            Why did I do it?
          </a>
        </h4>
      </div>
      <div id="collapseTwo" class="panel-collapse collapse">
        <div class="panel-body">
          <p>When I first came across the idea of the Johari window, I thought it would be great to try it with my friends. However,
            the technique poses three major flaws: 1) It requires to be physically close to someone 2) the responses might be
            biased, since it's difficult to keep them anonymous and 3) all the adjectives of the survey have a possitive connotation.
          <p>While looking online to solve these two problems, I found an <a href="http://kevan.org/johari" target="_blank">online service</a>
            that was solving two of these problems. It was online, thus you didn't have to be close to those taking the survey, and 
            the responses were anonymous. However, the problem of a limited selection of words was still there. That's why I thought of
            creating an online interactive application that would solve the third problem as well.</p>
          <p>This application comes with a pre-selected list of negative words (derived from
            <a href="http://www.managing-change.net/johari-window-model.html" target="_blank">here</a>) as well as the possibility for the users to add their own
            words, that might not be included in the pre-defined list. Thus, the bias towards the positive aspects of a person is removed.
            Due to usability of the application though, only a random subset of 40 words are used each time the page is visited.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel panel-default">
